	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>SPS dispute resolution and trans-Atlantic trade agreements </h1>

			
			<h4>
												15 December 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The recently concluded Canada–EU trade agreement includes provisions dealing with both sanitary and phytosanity (SPS) measures and dispute settlement. Both parties have committed themselves to building on existing WTO SPS commitments and, according to a Canadian government briefing, making “SPS provisions subject to dispute settlement”. In this context, a Sanitary and Phytosanitary Measures Joint Management Committee of experts is to be established “to discuss issues before they become problems, as well as facilitate discussions to resolve issues impeding trade”. </p><p>According to the Canadian government summary, the dispute settlement provisions are the “most efficient and innovative process for state-to-state dispute settlement of any of Canada’s free trade agreements”. Dispute settlement under the agreement is “significantly shorter than [the] WTO dispute resolution process” and “includes a single short process to determine whether a party has complied with a decision”. It also indicates a process “to prevent a party from blocking a dispute”. For dispute settlement, a number of sub-committees are to be established under the overall trade committee: the sub-committee on goods will be mandated to deal with SPS measures, among many other areas. </p><p>However the Canadian government summary notes that “[measures] necessary to protect human, animal, or plant life or health, or relating to the conservation of exhaustible natural resources” are exempt from dispute settlement arrangements established under the agreement. </p><p>In addition, existing Canada–EU veterinary agreements are to be updated and incorporated into the agreement, while a number of specific agreements have been reached on trade in red meats related to meat treatments permitted. Canada and the EU have also agreed to “proactively determine equivalency of each other’s inspection and certification systems”. </p><p>The importance of these SPS provisions was implicitly highlighted in comments from the US Meat Exporters Federation (USMEF) on the beef sector provisions of the agreement. Analysts at USMEF argued that while the tariff-rate quota (TRQ) gains “look good on paper, the actual impact may fall short of expectations”. It is argued that for real market access to be gained, the EU will need to make changes to its restrictions on the hormones and other practices that are a feature of north American livestock production. According to the USMEF analysis, a range of technical issues still need to addressed if they are not to continue to constitute technical barriers to trade. It was pointed out that while Canada has enjoyed access to the EU’s shared duty-free quota for high-quality grain-fed beef for 4 years, only 444 tonnes of Canadian beef was exported to the EU in 2013. However, it was acknowledged that “greater duty-free access” potentially “offsets the additional costs of serving this unique market”, allowing more producers and processors to capitalise on high-value market opportunities in the EU. </p><p>According to analysis published in October 2013 by the Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy (IATP), there is major concern in the US over the EU’s approach to food safety and SPS issues, which is rooted in the precautionary principle. US business interests see the precautionary principle as “unscientific and grounded more in politics than sound policy”. US exporters are therefore pressing for SPS and food safety measures to be “subject to challenge under investor–state dispute resolution”, an approach firmly rejected by IATP.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>CBC, ‘EU-Canada (summary, 2013)’, 29 October 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/summary-of-canada-eu-free-trade-deal-tabled-1.2286695" target="_self">http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/summary-of-canada-eu-free-trade-deal-tab...</a></p><p>Canada-European Union Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement, ‘Technical summary of final negotiated outcomes’, agreement-in-principle as of 18 October 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.bilaterals.org/spip.php?article24069&amp;lang=en" target="_self">http://www.bilaterals.org/spip.php?article24069&amp;lang=en</a></p><p><i>Beef Magazine</i>, ‘Canadian beef makes gains in EU agreement, but US must aim higher’, 31 October 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.bilaterals.org/spip.php?article24079&amp;lang=en#sthash.oTZAGcX2.dpuf" target="_self">http://www.bilaterals.org/spip.php?article24079&amp;lang=en#sthash.oTZAG...</a></p><p>Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy (IATP), ‘Promises and perils of the TTIP: Negotiating a transatlantic agricultural market’, by K. Hansen-Kuhn and S. Suppan, October 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.iatp.org/files/2013_10_25_TTIP_KHK.pdf" target="_self">http://www.iatp.org/files/2013_10_25_TTIP_KHK.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The extent to which SPS provisions are subject to dispute settlement under the Canada–EU agreement will be critically determined by the extent to which such measures are deemed to be “necessary to protect human, animal, or plant life or health”, since these are exempt from dispute settlement processes. Where fundamental differences of approach exist (e.g. the EU’s application of the precautionary approach, which places emphasis on proving the safety of products, rather than assuming them to be safe unless proven otherwise), little change is likely to occur.</p><p>Nevertheless, the establishment of an SPS Joint Management Committee of experts “to discuss issues before they become problems” and “facilitate discussions to resolve issues impeding trade”, as well as the inclusion of SPS measures in the mandate of the Trade Committee’s sub-committee on goods, holds out the promise of a new approach to dealing with SPS disputes through bilateral trade agreements. </p><p>Should progress be made in this area under the Canada–EU trade agreement, ACP governments may wish to seek the establishment of a similar binding mechanism for SPS dispute settlement.</p><p>The credibility of the new institutional mechanism is important, given the pressures in the US to subject SPS and food safety disputes to challenge under investor–state dispute resolution provisions. This is an option which is firmly resisted in the EU. In this context establishing a credible alternative mechanism for SPS and food safety dispute settlement resolution can be seen as important to the overall future of the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership negotiations.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
